title: For Sale:  Russian Hi-Capacity MAKAROV Pistol W/3 Mags, Ammo & Holster
postcontent:
For sale today is a rather rare & tough to find Hi-Capacity (double stack) Makarov pistol made in Russia by Imez and imported into the USA by KBI during the mid-90's. KBI brought in a fair amount of the standard 8 round Russian (single stack) Makarovs, but not nearly as many of the Hi-Cap models like this one.

I am the original owner and this pistol has been fired, but not much. It is in excellent condition and the bore is "mirror" bright. Pistol fires the standard 9x18 Makarov round and operates with a 10 round double stack magazine making total capacity 11 rounds (10+1). The Russian pistols are not finished quite as nicely as the East German ones, however in terms of accuracy, durability, and reliability they are at least as good if not better. I've always been amazed at how well this pistol shoots given it's size, and I am able to hit 12 oz. soda cans at 25 yards with little effort. If you have ever wondered whether our Comrades to the East are at any disadvantage as it pertains to small arms - trust me they are not!

Pistol comes in it's original box with manual, warranty card, safety info and hang tag. Also included is the multi-tool and cleaning rod it was shipped with. Additionally price includes 3 hi-cap magazines which are routinely selling for as much as $100 each on Gunbroker & Ebay when you can find them. There is also a "period style" leather holster with matching lanyard strap included and both are in excellent shape. Finally price includes 250 rounds of Silver Bear FMJ ammo which is produced at the Barnaul Cartridge Plant in Barnaul Russia. This ammo has a zinc plated case and it is excellent "blasting" ammo.

Price for everything listed above is $675. FTF with pickup in the Brandon area. You must be a Florida resident and at least 21 to purchase. Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  LNIB Tanfoglio 9mm Full Size Witness-P
postcontent:
This is probably one of the most versatile weapons listed on Armslist today.  Most people have not heard of Tanfoglio, but I have been buying and shooting these quality Italian guns for over 2 years and without exception they are as good or better than any Glock or XD out there.

These are CZ style double/single action weapons.  They have exposed hammers (unlike striker fire pistols like Glock) that can be cocked and locked with the safety engaged and ready for action.  The factory trigger is very crisp and the weapon is nicely balanced without relying on a full magazine to do so.

One of the features that makes Tanfoglio weapons so desirable is the fact that they can be modified easily with a number of conversion kits.  EAA makes kits for about $200 each that can convert this 9mm pistol to .22, .40, .45, and NATO 10mm.  With a Tanfoglio pistol you master handling one gun body (one grip, one set of sights, etc..) and can have 5 calibers to shoot from.  The conversion kits ship from Cape Canaveral, Florida and have always been in stock whenever I have called for them.

This is the Polymer full-size version of the Witness and has had literally 50 rounds put through it.  The results are displayed in the images.  I am not a fan of polymer guns like Glocks and XDs because I dont like the feel of the molded plastic in my hand.

But because I love Tanfoglio, I decided to try their Polymer Witness.  Surprise, surprise, it feels like a polymer gun!  If you are comfortable with XD or Glock, you will be at home here.  Its just not my thing.

I am selling this because I bought the steel version of this exact gun.  I love the brand, love the ease of modification, but just don't like polymer.  When you buy this I would love to show off my Tanfoglio collection and how the conversion kits work.  
It is all VERY VERY easy and makes a great shooting system for a reasonable price.

Call or text REDACTED with questions or to purchase the weapon.

title: For Sale:  Difference between a Magazine and a Clip
location: Learn as you go, Charleston, South Carolina
postcontent:
Terminology... Magazine or Clip: 
 In small arms terms magazine usually refers to a box, drum or tube with a spring inside to help feed the rounds. Magazines can be a fixed part of the weapon, or detachable. Most detachable magazines (often referred to as a clip, although this is technically inaccurate) can be removed and replaced with a full one to reload the weapon, but there are guns such as the Lee Enfield where the magazine is only removed for cleaning, and is refilled by a different mechanism. (more of this in a moment).

 The ammo Clip was invented in 1885 by Mannlicher and provided a way to place a full load of rounds into a magazine in one action. What many people do not appreciate is that the Clip also forms an integral part of the gun's mechanism. If the rounds are not held in a Clip the gun cannot go through the full cycle of chamber, fire and eject.
